  "prompt": "Do satellites emit color when viewed in the night sky?",
  "response": "Satellites themselves do not emit color when viewed in the night sky. They are typically visible due to the reflection of sunlight off their surfaces. This reflected light can appear as a steady, white or slightly yellowish point of light moving across the sky. The color may vary slightly depending on the materials of the satellite and the angle of the sun's reflection, but they do not emit their own colored light.",
